Phase IV: Nabataean Grand Design: 1st c. BCE to CE 1st c. The tetrastyle in antis temple is built, including the Porch extension, stylobate, Porch columns, East, West and South Corridor walls, East and West Walkway Walls and the East and West Porch Antae. Additionally, the limestone flooring from Phase II is extended at this time to cover the surfaces of the new corridors and walkways.
Bottom elevation: 3.60 m below Point E or 886.01 m.

This Part III West Corridor Wall is comprised of seven courses of ashlars bonded with mortar. It lies to the south of Locus 11 the south Doorjamb and ends in the south on the exterior with a course of well-set ashlars. (On the interior of the West Corridor, it continues to form a corner that is plastered.) There are 23 Mason’s Marks on the face of the ashlars comprising this wall. Letters include the Nabataean T, B, A, S, L or M, and SH. All the subject marks are recorded on the 1999 drawings #2 and 3.

Part I) Construction of the West Corridor Wall Locus 2 and Doorway 3 Doorjambs, Loci 4, 5 and Threshold Locus 14; Part II) Construction of the West Corridor Wall Locus 8; Part III) Doorway 4, and Doorjamb Locus 12. Locus 14 — Threshold Block between Doorjambs Loci 4 and 5 of Doorway 3, Part II. Locus 17 — Threshold Block between Locus 11 south and Locus 12 north.
